If you’re speaking symbolically, I can see why you’d draw the connection.

Electrons are difficult to see directly, yet they are involved in nearly everything we experience: chemistry, electricity, light interactions, computation, nerve signals. They are invisible carriers that help animate the material world.

In Christian theology, the Holy Spirit is often described as an unseen presence that moves, inspires, guides, animates, and connects. So at the level of metaphor, someone might say:

* Matter gives form.
* Electrons provide movement and interaction within matter.
* The Holy Spirit represents the unseen animating principle within spiritual life.

But that’s a metaphor, not a scientific or theological equivalence.

From a scientific perspective, electrons are physical particles (or quantum excitations, depending on the framework) that can be measured and described mathematically.

From a Christian perspective, the Holy Spirit is understood as God—not a physical substance or particle, but a divine person of the Trinity.

What’s interesting is that humans often reach for the same imagery across domains: wind, breath, fire, light, current, flow, spirit. Those metaphors appear because they describe things that are real in their effects but difficult to grasp directly.

The Greek word pneuma (spirit) can also mean breath or wind. You can’t see the wind itself—you see what it moves. Likewise, you don’t see an electron with your eyes—you see traces of its effects. That similarity has inspired many symbolic comparisons over the centuries, even though the concepts belong to very different categories.

So if you’re saying “Electrons are the Holy Spirit,” I’d interpret that less as a physics claim and more as a poetic attempt to point at an unseen force known through its manifestations.